external_knowledge:
- The GDP per capita is calculated by dividing the GDP by the population of a country;
- The average GDP of a region is the mean GDP of all countries within that region;
- The most recent data is determined by the latest year recorded in the dataset.

- "Population exceeding 30 million" refers to countries with a large population base;
- "Fertility rate below 2.5" indicates a low birth rate, often associated with developed or rapidly developing countries;
- "Life expectancy over 75 years" suggests a high standard of living and healthcare;
- "GDP per capita above $15,000" indicates a relatively high economic prosperity;
- "Poverty rate below 20%" suggests a low level of economic hardship among the population.

sql:
SELECT AVG(food) AS average_food_consumption, AVG(housing) AS average_housing_consumption
FROM consumption_patterns
WHERE country_id = 1;

external_knowledge:
- The "top decile income" refers to the daily income/consumption of the top 10% of the population;
- The "poverty rate" is the percentage of the population living below the poverty line;
- The "GDP per capita" is the total GDP divided by the population of the country.

- "same neighborhood" refers to the same region;
- "economic heartbeat has been strong" refers to countries with a GDP above 10,000;
- "recent past" refers to years after 2002.

- 'Prosperous region' refers to the region with the highest total GDP;
- 'Sum of its countries' wealth (GDP)' refers to the total GDP of all countries within the region;
- 'Balance between economic growth and income inequality' is represented by the average Gini coefficient, which measures income distribution within the region.

- "Bottom decile income" refers to the daily income or consumption of the poorest 10% of the population;
- "Global average" is the mean bottom decile income across all countries in the dataset;
- "Most recent year" is the latest year for which economic data is available for each country.

- A GDP of 1 trillion is a significant economic milestone, often associated with developed or rapidly developing economies;
- A life expectancy of 70 years is generally considered a marker of good health and living conditions;
- Inflation rate is a measure of the rate at which the general level of prices for goods and services is rising, and, subsequently, purchasing power is falling.

- 'artists' refers to users who have accessed the 'demographics' table;
- 'portrait of the land where the population grows like a line on a graph' refers to the visualization named 'Bulgaria Population Growth Line Graph';
- 'masterpieces' refers to the names of the visualizations.

- "Blooming" refers to countries that are economically thriving or growing;
- "Average GDP per capita exceeding $10,000" indicates a relatively high standard of living;
- "Total consumption" is the sum of percentages spent on various categories of consumption (food, housing, education, healthcare, transport, entertainment, and other items);
- "Human Development Index (HDI)" is a composite statistic used to rank countries based on human development levels.

- "economic dawn of the 1990s to 2000s" refers to the period from 1990 to 2000;
- "financial storms (inflation rates) surge above 2%" refers to an average inflation rate greater than 2%;
- "population growth (fertility rates) remained below 2.5 births per woman" refers to an average fertility rate less than 2.5.
